<paragraph pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia bigibbosa" order="Myrtales" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bigibbosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Conostegia bigibbosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was synonimized under 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="O. Berg ex Triana" authorityYear="1871" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia oerstediana" order="Myrtales" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oerstediana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Conostegia oerstediana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
and subsequently recognized by 
<bibRefCitation author="Almeda, F" journalOrPublisher="Flora Mesoamericana" pageId="239" pageNumber="240" pagination="164 - 338" refId="B8" refString="Almeda, F, 2009. Melastomataceae. Flora Mesoamericana vol. 4: 164 - 338" title="Melastomataceae." volume="vol. 4" year="2009">Almeda (2009)</bibRefCitation>
. I here recognize it based on geographic distribution and morphological characters. 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia bigibbosa" order="Myrtales" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bigibbosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Conostegia bigibbosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
always has pink petals as well as two tubercles on the petiole apex which makes it unmistakable. At one point, Schnell annotated it as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="O. Berg ex Triana" authorityYear="1871" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia oerstediana" order="Myrtales" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oerstediana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Conostegia oerstediana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which is allopatric and has white petals and lacks the two tubercles at the apex of the petiole. 
<bibRefCitation author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
carried out some crossing experiments between 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia bigibbosa" order="Myrtales" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bigibbosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Conostegia bigibbosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="O. Berg ex Triana" authorityYear="1871" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia oerstediana" order="Myrtales" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oerstediana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Conostegia oerstediana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia montana" order="Myrtales" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="montana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Conostegia montana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. He noted that fruit development was initiated when pollinating 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="O. Berg ex Triana" authorityYear="1871" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia oerstediana" order="Myrtales" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oerstediana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Conostegia oerstediana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with pollen of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia bigibbosa" order="Myrtales" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bigibbosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Conostegia bigibbosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but not with pollen of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia montana" order="Myrtales" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="montana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Conostegia montana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or when left unpollinated. Unfortunately he could not finish his experiment because the material was vandalized. The two species are not sympatric however and maintain the petal color difference as well as the petiole tubercle difference in natural populations.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
